  title: A Memorial Defending Sungnim Lee
  author: Kwon Geun
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Word reaches us that the Censorate recently submitted charges against Lee Sungnim, Vice Director of the Hall of Worthies, seeking to expose his alleged crimes. Your Highness, blessed with keen judgment and luminous wisdom, perceived his innocence and moved to restore him to favor and office. Yet the accusers only grew more zealous, proclaiming him both unfilial and disloyal. Reluctant to dismiss the remonstrations of your censors, Your Highness issued an edict removing him from office—thereby demonstrating the clarity and justice of your rule, and your virtue in heeding counsel. All admirable indeed. Yet when there exists a ruler as wise as Your Highness and a minister as worthy as Sungnim, and when such excellence falls to ruin under false and grave accusations, it is cause for deep lamentation. I cannot remain silent. Thus do I venture to speak, submitting my arguments for your consideration.

    The charge of unfilial conduct rests on this: that Sungnim assumed an examination position within three years of his mother's death. Yet his father, the late Yeongu, was aged and ailing, his life hanging by a thread. He yearned to witness his son assume this honored post before death claimed him. The state, recognizing Sungnim's talent and moved by the father's wish, petitioned the Prince Regent to grant him this appointment. Had Sungnim declined, he would have honored the dead mother while abandoning the living father—seeking to escape later reproach while disregarding his father's present wishes. Thus, though his heart was uneasy, he accepted the post. This is indeed a misfortune for a filial son—but cannot be called unfiliality. As the Master said, "Observe a man's faults, and you discern his goodness."

    Consider those in service today. Some hold the highest offices—judges who condemn men, officials who command executions—all while their parents lie dead these three years. For whom do they gain renown? For themselves alone. If abandoning comfort for a parent's sake is called unfilial, how can forgetting one's parents entirely be called true filial piety? Moreover, among our people, scarcely one in ten thousand truly observes three years of mourning. The state has even established the law of restoration to office, which lightens such observance. If Sungnim is punished, surely you must employ only those rare souls who kept the full period. Would Your Highness then cast away ten thousand to find one? I fear the realm would lack worthy men to serve.

    Should Sungnim's loving concern for his father go unrecognized, his name bearing only the stigma of unfiliality, is this not deeply lamentable?

    As for the charge of disloyalty: Sungnim was commanded to investigate the truth of certain matters concerning Yongheung. He should have responded at once, yet he delayed and eventually went into hiding. Yet here is the consideration: such matters of investigation are small verbal matters. By the state's ancient laws, a public inquiry would suffice—no more. Furthermore, the Censorate previously submitted a memorial stating that when great officials transgress the law, they should not be subjected to degrading punishment. Your Highness approved this principle and issued a judgment establishing it as precedent. Relying on both this ancient law and your judgment, Sungnim did not immediately come forward. Only when the Censorate grew angry and pressed the matter did he realize that neither the old law nor your judgment could shield him. Cornered and desperate, he withdrew. Though his hesitation showed weakness, it arose from faulty handling by his superiors, not from disloyalty in his heart or defiance of your command.

    Regarding the Yongheung matter itself: Sungnim's nature is gentle and compassionate, and he cherished his friendships deeply. He happened to live near Gaheung and others, heard their accounts, and accepted their words—he did not fabricate such claims. When his office was restored, his delay in coming to express gratitude arose from fear of the Censorate alone, not from disrespect toward your command.

    As for the rumor that he engaged in trade during his embassy to Ming: there are explanations. An official named Chen there was married to a relative of Sungnim's wife. When Sungnim visited his house and passed through the marketplace and streets—wishing merely to observe and appreciate the sights—certain enemies of Sungnim seized the moment to spread vicious calumny. Those who heard it, lacking discernment, accepted it as truth. If Sungnim truly engaged in commerce to the state's dishonor, surely I would have heard of it during my own embassy, which came after his return. Yet throughout my time in Ming, I never once heard such allegations. How then could those at home, whose feet have never touched Ming soil, claim to know what their ears have never heard? Are these accusers more capable than Sungnim himself? Should we believe slanderers' words while doubting the conduct of a worthy man? This is gravely unjust.

    Consider Sungnim's actual service to the state. Since our nation began formal relations with Ming, most official documents and diplomatic dispatches have come from his hand. The posthumous honor granted to King Gongmin, the confirmation of the Prince Regent's title—both owed to Sungnim's literary talents. The remission of annual tribute in gold, silver, horses, and hemp—this too was his accomplishment. The Ming Emperor has repeatedly praised our literary excellence and acknowledged that our nation possesses men of talent—acknowledgment flowing from Sungnim's pen. His writing is concise and ancient in its nobility, appearing once in generations. Even in Ming it is rare. The state cannot afford to entrust its diplomatic voice to any but this man.

    Yet the accusers heed not his contributions. They believe the whispered poison of lesser men and dare to level grave charges against him. Is this not deeply to be regretted?

    Affection for kinfolk and respect for the worthy are the two great principles by which realm and state are governed. Your Highness has already shown filial concern by personally championing the Prince Regent and commanding an investigation into the Yongheung matter. This demonstrates perfection in the first principle. Yet Sungnim, who served long as your tutor in reading, merits the same diligence. Mere rumor was sufficient for his dismissal, without even a hearing. The second principle remains incomplete.

    I humbly grieve for Your Highness in this. Issue a command to investigate: let the accusers prove their claims in detail. If they charge that Sungnim trafficked in goods, demand an accounting: how many carts, how many horses, and were they all laden exclusively with his merchandise, exceeding the proper measure? Should the investigation reveal that the accusers themselves purchased nothing, that the carts bore no goods uniquely his, and that the horses bore no excess—then the accusers stand revealed as slanderers of a worthy man. Punish their defamation accordingly, and Sungnim's honor is vindicated. All the world will praise Your Highness's justice.

    Conversely, should the investigation reveal that the accusers purchased goods freely, that carts were not exclusively Sungnim's, and that horses bore no excess, then Sungnim stands innocent, and ten thousand generations will acclaim your luminous wisdom.

    Other accusers argue that Sungnim, being learned and of established reputation, cannot be judged as ordinary men. Though his faults be minor, they deserve the severest punishment. How lacking in reflection this is! When those void of learning and useless to the state transgress, we deem it trifling and offer protection. Yet when those of literary talent and service to the realm commit small errors, we pronounce them unforgivable and press toward their ruin. What then shall posterity do? All will seek merely to escape blame through shamelessness, none will labor at learning or seek understanding, for what good comes from gaining reputation and reaping ruin?

    This corrupts the hearts of men and dispirits the scholar's purpose—a grave harm indeed.

    Since ancient times, there has been a principle regarding the learned, the capable, and the meritorious: when such men err, judgment should follow the principle of mitigation—not to excuse wrongdoing, but to encourage all men to strive for excellence. Yet modern accusers ignore this wisdom. They burden the worthy and capable with harsh judgment, thereby discouraging virtue in those who follow.

    Should Your Highness, weighing Sungnim's literary contributions, grant him lenience despite his faults, posterity would take heart in learning. How much more so, when as I have shown, his supposed crimes bear examination and prove defensible.

    I humbly beseech Your Highness: forward this memorial to the Bureau of Consolidated Deliberation, the Secretariat, and the Censorate. Let them investigate the accusers, reveal the truth, vindicate the wronged, honor the worthy, elevate scholarly virtue, and encourage those who follow. Thus public justice is upheld and the state preserved.

    In ages past, even the Duke of Zhou and Confucius—greatest of sages—were not spared from error and calumny. Had Mencius not defended Kuangzhang's filial piety, it would have remained in question. Had the hostel-keeper not vouched for Su Bu, the charge of theft would have clung to him. Even the ancient sages faced undeserved reproach. I humbly ask: let not mere accusation move Your Highness to dismiss Sungnim.

    If Your Highness deems my words without merit, I accept that these matters be given to the appropriate officials, and that I myself be punished for advocating improperly for a friend. I would gladly accept grave censure alongside Sungnim—death itself would bring no regret. I cannot sit silent while a worthy man, wronged by false accusation, faces ruin. Fear of office and of power cannot keep me mute. Thus do I presume to offer these humble, imperfect words.
  footnotes:
    - '末減 (末減): A legal principle by which, among multiple charges, the lightest penalty is imposed. Here, Kwon argues that when worthy and capable men commit minor errors, leniency should follow this principle to encourage virtue.'
    - 'The Duke of Zhou and Confucius: Historical references to ancient sages who, despite their wisdom, faced false accusations—supporting Kwon''s argument that even the greatest men may be slandered and therefore should not be hastily judged.'
    - 'The Yongheung matter: Likely refers to a dispute concerning a family member or ally of the Prince Regent, whose legitimacy or conduct Sungnim was asked to investigate.'
    - 'Ming dynasty diplomatic relations: Sungnim''s prominence in state correspondence reflects Korea''s tributary status toward Ming China during this period.'
